[{"sha":"6a85a4dde678e5b91b983871cfb81ac31759aa57","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Make a copy of FlatLAF's tab displayer classes, for use with the Windows LAF.

This commit is part of NETBEANS-5673, which modernizes the look of NetBeans'
window system tabs on the Windows LAF, and makes the tabs look good on various
HiDPI resolutions. I decided to use the FlatLAF tab displayer implementations as
a starting point for the new look rather than the old Windows LAF
implementations, as FlatLAF already handles HiDPI scaling, and has convenient
configuration settings.

This commit does a "clean" copy of a few files from the o.n.swing.laf.flatlaf
module to the o.n.swing.tabcontrol module, only doing as much refactoring as
necessary to avoid dependencies on the actual external FlatLAF library and its
configuration files. Configuration constants are added to Windows8LFCustoms,
initially matching those of FlatLAF Light. In the next commits, I will customize
the configuration and tab displayer implementations to actually look like
Windows 10 style tabs.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/6a85a4dde678e5b91b983871cfb81ac31759aa57"},{"sha":"684368f42bc4399d71b2d7ca6c872e3907f017f0","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Various improvements to Windows LAF tab painting logic; part of NETBEANS-5673.

This commit contains various improvements to the tab painting classes that were
copied to the Windows LAF from FlatLAF in the previous commit. These particular
changes may later be ported back to FlatLAF if desired. In this commit, we do
not yet change the actual styling of the tabs.

Details:
* Align and connect borders between tabs and the container panel below,
  including on fractional HiDPI scalings (e.g. 150%). Some visual artifacts
  still exist, e.g. on 125% scaling, but they are less common, and not very
  visible.
* Improve the behavior of DPIUnscaledBorder in more cases.
* Add new configuration options to the TabDisplayerUI classes, to prepare for
  the new tab style on Windows, but do not yet make use of them. This includes
  the ability to draw a border around the selected tab, the ability to set a
  separate hover color for unselected tabs, and support for a color gradient in
  the selected editor tab.
* In editor tabs, avoid showing a tab separator after the last tab.
* In editor tabs, properly handle clipped tabs.
* In view tabs, properly allocate space for the animated "busy" icon.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/684368f42bc4399d71b2d7ca6c872e3907f017f0"},{"sha":"df0cada60669664507d0266314d7b76728d92308","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Replace the bitmap 'busy' icon with a manually drawn spinner that scales well on HiDPI/Retina screens.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/df0cada60669664507d0266314d7b76728d92308"},{"sha":"ad7eea77d996624caf520aa32cfced8250848882","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Adjust some borders on the Windows LAF, and other smaller tweaks.

Details:
* Apply previous border tweaks for HiDPI screens in a few more places, notably
  in tooltips and the quick search text field, and in the editor toolbar.
  Improve JSpinner borders.
* Make the background color of tooltips consistent with that of other Windows 10
  apps.
* Add some pixels of left margin to the editor toolbar.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/ad7eea77d996624caf520aa32cfced8250848882"},{"sha":"04d363bb5ea2493747bce4e152c4e23f86802236","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Apply Windows LAF HiDPI bug workarounds from NETBEANS-3592 to JCheckboxMenuItem and friends.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/04d363bb5ea2493747bce4e152c4e23f86802236"},{"sha":"b1d9f919ec0a5eb7301c74b1f7216d9aeb7c84e6","author":{"name":"Jan Lahoda","email":"f0e6c8b88151cef643d02fd650fc0b650ee35a7f@netbeans.org"},"message":"[NETBEANS-4953] Fixing handling of WSL-based URIs.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/b1d9f919ec0a5eb7301c74b1f7216d9aeb7c84e6"},{"sha":"913a5cbef1af55f7f7d9dd238034c470076f3b86","author":{"name":"Gaurav Gupta","email":"8127a206c55a088f6d4afbad34cfcf8237a825b2@payara.fish"},"message":"NETBEANS-5143 Fixes Maven web app twice deployment issue","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/913a5cbef1af55f7f7d9dd238034c470076f3b86"},{"sha":"3117964b0b708d8fba3b404e2a75312942368e51","author":{"name":"Jose Contreras","email":"d187f796b0009c623e22c11185625249ec6a6f1f@gmail.com"},"message":"Update asm from 8.0.1 to 9.2

[{"sha":"063ec6a82f0b8dbc7d2215d18e80c06ee5d57141","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Clean-up: Move Offscreen logic from Suspense fiber

Much of the visibility-toggling logic is shared between the Suspense and
Offscreen types, but there is some duplicated code that exists in both.
Specifically, when a Suspense fiber's state switches from suspended to
resolved, we schedule an effect on the parent Suspense fiber, rather
than the inner Offscreen fiber. Then in the commit phase, the Suspense
fiber is responsible for committing the visibility effect on Offscreen.

There two main reasons we implemented it this way, neither of which
apply any more:

- The inner Offscreen fiber that wraps around the Suspense children used
  to be conditionally added only when the boundary was in its fallback
  state. So when toggling back to visible, there was no inner fiber to
  handle the visibility effect. This is no longer the case — the
  primary children are always wrapped in an Offscreen fiber.
- When the Suspense fiber is in its fallback state, the inner Offscreen
  fiber does not have a complete phase, because we bail out of
  rendering that tree. In the old effects list implementation, that
  meant the Offscreen fiber did not get added to the effect list, so
  it didn't have a commit phase. In the new recursive effects
  implementation, there's no list to maintain. Marking a flag on the
  inner fiber is sufficient to schedule a commit effect.

Given that these are no relevant, I was able to remove a lot of old
code and shift more of the logic out of the Suspense implementation
and into the Offscreen implementation so that it is shared by both.
(Being able to share the implementaiton like this was in fact one of
the reasons we stopped conditionally removing the inner
Offscreen fiber.)

As a bonus, this happens to fix a TODO in the Offscreen implementation
for persistent (Fabric) mode, where newly inserted nodes inside an
already hidden tree must also be hidden. Though we'll still need to
make this work in mutation (DOM) mode, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/063ec6a82f0b8dbc7d2215d18e80c06ee5d57141"}]

The issue was the tensor_float_32_enabled global variable was being linked in the binary twice. Disabling TensorFloat-32 changed one version of the global variable, and OpKernels checking TensorFloat-32 looked at the other version of the global variable. @penpornk helped find the fix.

I confirmed this change fixes the issue when applied to commit 2903b0a7d133a15d71d513df826386dc28d0631f. Unfortunately, the tests did not catch this issue, as the test case in config_test.py currently only supports Ampere and is skipped for non-Ampere GPUs (TensorFloat-32 only supports Ampere). I will later add a test that will catch such issues even when run on non-Ampere GPUs.

I plan on cherry-picking this change into TF 2.6.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385560452
Change-Id: I5b19c1a78a71e3e6e33689e1576693b78ae0543a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/coneco/tensorflow/commits/fc55e3af01e239b0fcdf9d9e6c21cf99476feb29"},{"sha":"cf8a6bd57e9215f7d1d3face5a5e1fb78828c122","author":{"name":"Tim Shen","email":"4730ecb3b3122c1a4c40822c62fa6d402a094d1b@google.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Generate `lmhlo.fusion { mhlo.some_op }` instead of `lmhlo.some_op`, for most of the ops.

This simplifies the emitter for quite a bit, as kCopy and kReduce emitters now don't have to deal with unnested cases.

This also simplifies XLA HLO -> LMHLO conversion, since now there are much less kinds of LMHLO ops to be converted.

Per chat discussion between sanjoy@, jurahul@ and me, we think it's a good idea to move away from LMHLO and only use lmhlo.fusion + MHLO. This way, lmhlo.fusion effectively just acts as a composable bufferization annotation.

This CL is a preliminary experiment for that plan, as it removes some uses from XLA/GPU. Once we are confident about this approach, we can officially propose the deprecation and removal of LMHLO (except for .fusion).

[{"sha":"0f9198f4feb78a326b6cc92b0996d8cb6dcdd23f","author":{"name":"Srishti Srivastava","email":"904a07f5d5a3adde1e4d458a4465bbe1e0df36dc@polymagelabs.com"},"message":"[MLIR][TF] Canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan

Added and used a template to canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan.
When the divisor/multiplier of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is
a constant with all the elements in its tensor (with float/complex type)
being zero, tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with its
divisor/multiplier, respectively. Further, when the divisor/multiplier
of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is a constant with all the
elements in its tensor (with float/complex type) being non-zero,
tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with tf.Div/tf.Mul, respectively.
Relevant test cases are added as well.

Signed-off-by: Srishti Srivastava <srishti.srivastava@polymagelabs.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/srishti-pm/tensorflow/commits/0f9198f4feb78a326b6cc92b0996d8cb6dcdd23f"}]

Change-Id: Ie35c222a30d257c4ef3226fb602abc0ef40fd6ff","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Aurelius84/tensorflow/commits/d2abe16288dce4a730d4a13cb1ab6cdedfc6b998"},{"sha":"1f696e799119c70bbb1ed2b70500af5ece457f75","author":{"name":"Hanhan Wang","email":"17db91a825a40156b2c20ef2022824cbafd12aac@google.com"},"message":"Lowering mhlo.reduce_window to Linalg ops for dynamic shapes.

Also fixes the input shape for static test cases. E.g.,

```
  %0 = "mhlo.reduce_window"(%arg0, %arg1) ( {
  ^bb0(%arg2: tensor<f32>, %arg3 : tensor<f32>):
    %1 = mhlo.minimum %arg2, %arg3 : tensor<f32>
    "mhlo.return"(%1) : (tensor<f32>) -> ()
  }) {window_dimensions = dense<[1, 3, 3, 1]> : tensor<4xi64>,
      window_strides = dense<[1, 2, 2, 1]> : tensor<4xi64>} : (tensor<1x17x17x64xf32>, tensor<f32>) -> tensor<1x8x8x64xf32>
```

Look into dimension 1 where window_dim is 3 and window_stride is 2.
The reduction indices are [0, 3), [2, 5), ... , [14, 17).
In this case, 17 is enough for input size. The last element will never
get touched.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385492367
Change-Id: I668b618e7b18abed199b445641b469069f35de2f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/1bec81a9f28005ef2e5cc9f3063fd62ce3272bdf"},{"sha":"62db2e9b5b3ed8c28a3170b0961480008048f4d0","author":{"name":"George Necula","email":"ff41ff8c67a16b3c7c1ec22e97a29c6fe4506fc6@google.com"},"message":"[host_callback] Increase number of threads for callback processing.

Previously there was one thread per device for receiving the outfeed from
devices, but there was a single global thread that was calling into the Python
callbacks. This meant that if one of the callbacks was slow, it was blocking
processing of all other callbacks.

One situation when this created difficulties was if one wanted to break a host_callback into two operations: a quick one to enqueue work on a threadpool,
and a subsequent slow one to wait for and retreive the result. The first slow callback would block all other callbacks, including possibly some quick ones, thus missing the opportunity to start the slow work.

With this change there is a separate queue of outfeeds for each device and a
separate thread per device to call into Python. This allows for concurrency
between callbacks from different devices, although the callbacks from one
device are still sequential. If the programmer wants more concurrency, they can use a threadpool. Having more concurrency by default is tricky, because it may mean that the Python callbacks for one device may be seen out of order.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385492367
Change-Id: I668b618e7b18abed199b445641b469069f35de2f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/1bec81a9f28005ef2e5cc9f3063fd62ce3272bdf"},{"sha":"62db2e9b5b3ed8c28a3170b0961480008048f4d0","author":{"name":"George Necula","email":"ff41ff8c67a16b3c7c1ec22e97a29c6fe4506fc6@google.com"},"message":"[host_callback] Increase number of threads for callback processing.

Previously there was one thread per device for receiving the outfeed from
devices, but there was a single global thread that was calling into the Python
callbacks. This meant that if one of the callbacks was slow, it was blocking
processing of all other callbacks.

One situation when this created difficulties was if one wanted to break a host_callback into two operations: a quick one to enqueue work on a threadpool,
and a subsequent slow one to wait for and retreive the result. The first slow callback would block all other callbacks, including possibly some quick ones, thus missing the opportunity to start the slow work.

With this change there is a separate queue of outfeeds for each device and a
separate thread per device to call into Python. This allows for concurrency
between callbacks from different devices, although the callbacks from one
device are still sequential. If the programmer wants more concurrency, they can use a threadpool. Having more concurrency by default is tricky, because it may mean that the Python callbacks for one device may be seen out of order.

This commit is part of NETBEANS-5673, which modernizes the look of NetBeans'
window system tabs on the Windows LAF, and makes the tabs look good on various
HiDPI resolutions. I decided to use the FlatLAF tab displayer implementations as
a starting point for the new look rather than the old Windows LAF
implementations, as FlatLAF already handles HiDPI scaling, and has convenient
configuration settings.

This commit does a "clean" copy of a few files from the o.n.swing.laf.flatlaf
module to the o.n.swing.tabcontrol module, only doing as much refactoring as
necessary to avoid dependencies on the actual external FlatLAF library and its
configuration files. Configuration constants are added to Windows8LFCustoms,
initially matching those of FlatLAF Light. In the next commits, I will customize
the configuration and tab displayer implementations to actually look like

This commit contains various improvements to the tab painting classes that were
copied to the Windows LAF from FlatLAF in the previous commit. These particular
changes may later be ported back to FlatLAF if desired. In this commit, we do
not yet change the actual styling of the tabs.

Details:
* Align and connect borders between tabs and the container panel below,
  including on fractional HiDPI scalings (e.g. 150%). Some visual artifacts
  still exist, e.g. on 125% scaling, but they are less common, and not very
  visible.
* Improve the behavior of DPIUnscaledBorder in more cases.
* Add new configuration options to the TabDisplayerUI classes, to prepare for
  the new tab style on Windows, but do not yet make use of them. This includes
  the ability to draw a border around the selected tab, the ability to set a
  separate hover color for unselected tabs, and support for a color gradient in
  the selected editor tab.
* In editor tabs, avoid showing a tab separator after the last tab.
* In editor tabs, properly handle clipped tabs.
* In view tabs, properly allocate space for the animated "busy" icon.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jGauravGupta/netbeans/commits/684368f42bc4399d71b2d7ca6c872e3907f017f0"},{"sha":"df0cada60669664507d0266314d7b76728d92308","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Replace the bitmap 'busy' icon with a manually drawn spinner that scales well on HiDPI/Retina screens.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jGauravGupta/netbeans/commits/df0cada60669664507d0266314d7b76728d92308"},{"sha":"ad7eea77d996624caf520aa32cfced8250848882","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Adjust some borders on the Windows LAF, and other smaller tweaks.

Split some parts of NativeInterpreterWrapper which depend on experimental APIs
into a separate derived class NativeInterpreterWrapperExperimental,
and don't include that derived class in the "stable" build targets.

In particular NativeInterpreterWrapper.resetVariableTensors depends on
the C++ Interpreter::ResetVariableTensors method, which is experimental,
so we want to avoid depending on that from the "stable" build targets.

(Note that parts which depend on Interpreter::ModifyGraphWithDelegate
have NOT been moved to NativeInterpreterWrapperExperimental. The tentative
plan for those is to instead refactor them to use InterpreterBuilder::AddDelegate, and to promote that API to stable, in subsequent CLs.)

Change-Id: I8a3e0ef9e573b75b9429facda0fc4fb2e92a869a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/c891adef52607b9c65bb190fb55d794a95fe30e8"},{"sha":"69fc036bb636ea7f76d4b4d879e27f7e4cf0ad33","author":{"name":"Peng Wang","email":"b55f18ff6423501a9509f40f9539fd4a14e4c9f9@google.com"},"message":"Adds automatic ref-counting (on the underlying resource) to ResourceHandle.

This CL adds an option for ResourceHandle to hold on to a pointer to a resource, in which case the ResourceHandle will call `Ref` on the resource when the handle is copied, and call `Unref` on the resource when the handle is destroyed. This feature will serve as an automatic life-cycle management system for resources.

Resources under this life-cycle management system will bypass ResourceMgr.

This CL doesn't opt in any existing resources to this new life-cycle management system. Follow-up CLs will opt them in gradually.

[{"sha":"6bdec787aa1e31cce712f8fd31a91b8902988f52","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Fix bug where operands were incorrectly replaced for outside compiled ops with dynamic shapes.

This occurred when an outside compiled op with non-dynamic output came before another outside compiled op with a dynamic output.  For example:

%7 = "tf.E"(%4, %3) {_xla_outside_compilation = "auto"} : (tensor<?xi32>, tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<2xi32>)
%8 = "tf.F"(%7) : (tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<2xi32>)
%9 = "tf.G"(%8, %4, %3) {_xla_outside_compilation = "auto"} : (tensor<2xi32>, tensor<?xi32>, tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<?xi32>)

In this case, the second op should have all of the inputs sent to host through XlaHostCompute op so that shape inference works correctly.  With the bug, the statically shaped inputs were provided by communication for the earlier outside compilation op.  This lead to overwriting the value in the earlier op leading to a "operand #1 does not dominate this use" error.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385492367
Change-Id: I668b618e7b18abed199b445641b469069f35de2f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sakib-rahman-bangladesh/tensorflow/commits/1bec81a9f28005ef2e5cc9f3063fd62ce3272bdf"},{"sha":"62db2e9b5b3ed8c28a3170b0961480008048f4d0","author":{"name":"George Necula","email":"ff41ff8c67a16b3c7c1ec22e97a29c6fe4506fc6@google.com"},"message":"[host_callback] Increase number of threads for callback processing.

Previously there was one thread per device for receiving the outfeed from
devices, but there was a single global thread that was calling into the Python
callbacks. This meant that if one of the callbacks was slow, it was blocking
processing of all other callbacks.

One situation when this created difficulties was if one wanted to break a host_callback into two operations: a quick one to enqueue work on a threadpool,
and a subsequent slow one to wait for and retreive the result. The first slow callback would block all other callbacks, including possibly some quick ones, thus missing the opportunity to start the slow work.

With this change there is a separate queue of outfeeds for each device and a
separate thread per device to call into Python. This allows for concurrency
between callbacks from different devices, although the callbacks from one
device are still sequential. If the programmer wants more concurrency, they can use a threadpool. Having more concurrency by default is tricky, because it may mean that the Python callbacks for one device may be seen out of order.

[{"sha":"9ab90de602357407fb03a27715b61761a258a8c4","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Clean-up: Move Offscreen logic from Suspense fiber (#21925)

Much of the visibility-toggling logic is shared between the Suspense and
Offscreen types, but there is some duplicated code that exists in both.
Specifically, when a Suspense fiber's state switches from suspended to
resolved, we schedule an effect on the parent Suspense fiber, rather
than the inner Offscreen fiber. Then in the commit phase, the Suspense
fiber is responsible for committing the visibility effect on Offscreen.

There two main reasons we implemented it this way, neither of which
apply any more:

- The inner Offscreen fiber that wraps around the Suspense children used
  to be conditionally added only when the boundary was in its fallback
  state. So when toggling back to visible, there was no inner fiber to
  handle the visibility effect. This is no longer the case — the
  primary children are always wrapped in an Offscreen fiber.
- When the Suspense fiber is in its fallback state, the inner Offscreen
  fiber does not have a complete phase, because we bail out of
  rendering that tree. In the old effects list implementation, that
  meant the Offscreen fiber did not get added to the effect list, so
  it didn't have a commit phase. In the new recursive effects
  implementation, there's no list to maintain. Marking a flag on the
  inner fiber is sufficient to schedule a commit effect.

Given that these are no relevant, I was able to remove a lot of old
code and shift more of the logic out of the Suspense implementation
and into the Offscreen implementation so that it is shared by both.
(Being able to share the implementaiton like this was in fact one of
the reasons we stopped conditionally removing the inner
Offscreen fiber.)

As a bonus, this happens to fix a TODO in the Offscreen implementation
for persistent (Fabric) mode, where newly inserted nodes inside an
already hidden tree must also be hidden. Though we'll still need to
make this work in mutation (DOM) mode, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/9ab90de602357407fb03a27715b61761a258a8c4"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385492367
Change-Id: I668b618e7b18abed199b445641b469069f35de2f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LongerVision/tensorflow/commits/1bec81a9f28005ef2e5cc9f3063fd62ce3272bdf"},{"sha":"62db2e9b5b3ed8c28a3170b0961480008048f4d0","author":{"name":"George Necula","email":"ff41ff8c67a16b3c7c1ec22e97a29c6fe4506fc6@google.com"},"message":"[host_callback] Increase number of threads for callback processing.

Previously there was one thread per device for receiving the outfeed from
devices, but there was a single global thread that was calling into the Python
callbacks. This meant that if one of the callbacks was slow, it was blocking
processing of all other callbacks.

One situation when this created difficulties was if one wanted to break a host_callback into two operations: a quick one to enqueue work on a threadpool,
and a subsequent slow one to wait for and retreive the result. The first slow callback would block all other callbacks, including possibly some quick ones, thus missing the opportunity to start the slow work.

With this change there is a separate queue of outfeeds for each device and a
separate thread per device to call into Python. This allows for concurrency
between callbacks from different devices, although the callbacks from one
device are still sequential. If the programmer wants more concurrency, they can use a threadpool. Having more concurrency by default is tricky, because it may mean that the Python callbacks for one device may be seen out of order.

`GetInput`, `GetVariableInput` and `GetOutput` all fail to check for the case where `node->inputs->data[index]` is the special `kTfLiteOptionalTensor` value (-1) which then causes `context->tensors[node->inputs->data[index]]` to read from invalid memory location.

This fix makes `GetInput` and related return `nullptr` in those cases, asking the caller to check for `nullptr`. This is better than having `GetOptionalInputTensor` and `GetOptionalOutputTensor` (does not exist but could be added) as using the patched `GetInput` in error would be caught by a sanitizer test in the default optimized build (due to the `-fsanitize=null` option).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 332512190
Change-Id: Iabca54da2f2de02b6ece3c38b54f76d4277d689e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Riveryh/tensorflow/commits/38cbad757b2e1c0d64b95e4582408fa66627a67c"},{"sha":"f911af101dc0ce0eec17a8740bec9b613ae4195e","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"[tflite] Make `GetOptionalInputTensor` the same as `GetInput`.

With the previous change, there is no more need for two separate APIs. We would deprecate `GetOptionalInputTensor` in the future.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 332513386
Change-Id: Id7110271c25ebd6126ad8c82a493e37e0e0756b3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Riveryh/tensorflow/commits/f911af101dc0ce0eec17a8740bec9b613ae4195e"},{"sha":"f4159ccef23d11eb58ee4263beaaeac1be3343c7","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"[tflite] Ensure inputs and outputs don't overlap.

If a model uses the same tensor for both an input and an output then this can result in data loss and memory corruption. This should not happen.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 332522916
Change-Id: If0905b142415a9dfceaf2d181872f2a8fb88f48a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Riveryh/tensorflow/commits/f4159ccef23d11eb58ee4263beaaeac1be3343c7"},{"sha":"37640ce42f195dc0b91ca0cc753793f80e43b289","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"[tflite] Ensure input tensors don't have `nullptr` buffers.

A crafted TFLite model can force a node to have as input a tensor backed by a `nullptr` buffer. That is, by carefully changing the buffer index in the flatbuffer serialization, we can force the TFLite interpreter to consider a read-only tensor to be a read-write one and assume that there is an operator that has this tensor as output, writing to it and allocating memory before the tensor is used as input. If this does not happen, we get memory corruption.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 332524692
Change-Id: I57ef175152a29020af9ab041dc959e5631dce40f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Riveryh/tensorflow/commits/37640ce42f195dc0b91ca0cc753793f80e43b289"},{"sha":"28a9887abefa982812d3c769b2c1e7578f32c7dd","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"[tflite] Ensure `MatchingDim` does not allow buffer overflow.

We check in `MatchingDim` that both arguments have the same dimensionality, however that is a `DCHECK` only enabled if building in debug mode. Hence, it could be possible to cause buffer overflows by passing in a tensor with larger dimensions as the second argument. To fix, we now make `MatchingDim` return the minimum of the two sizes.

A much better fix would be to return a status object but that requires refactoring a large part of the codebase for minor benefits.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 332526127
Change-Id: If627d0d2c80a685217b6e0d1e64b0872dbf1c5e4","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Riveryh/tensorflow/commits/28a9887abefa982812d3c769b2c1e7578f32c7dd"},{"sha":"8f97b7caffab7757782be2f19b6cd3e5c154432a","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"[tflite] Ensure `ResolveAxis` properly handles negative inputs.

In Python, a list `l` of length `n` allows indexing with negative indices, `l[i]`. The only constraint is that `n + i` becomes positive. Code in `ResolveAxis` assumes the constraints and only checks it using a `DCHECK`. But the macro is a no-op in non-debug builds and that can result in reading from negative offsets (buffer underflows).

This commit is part of NETBEANS-5673, which modernizes the look of NetBeans'
window system tabs on the Windows LAF, and makes the tabs look good on various
HiDPI resolutions. I decided to use the FlatLAF tab displayer implementations as
a starting point for the new look rather than the old Windows LAF
implementations, as FlatLAF already handles HiDPI scaling, and has convenient
configuration settings.

This commit does a "clean" copy of a few files from the o.n.swing.laf.flatlaf
module to the o.n.swing.tabcontrol module, only doing as much refactoring as
necessary to avoid dependencies on the actual external FlatLAF library and its
configuration files. Configuration constants are added to Windows8LFCustoms,
initially matching those of FlatLAF Light. In the next commits, I will customize
the configuration and tab displayer implementations to actually look like
Windows 10 style tabs.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jGauravGupta/netbeans/commits/6a85a4dde678e5b91b983871cfb81ac31759aa57"},{"sha":"684368f42bc4399d71b2d7ca6c872e3907f017f0","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Various improvements to Windows LAF tab painting logic; part of NETBEANS-5673.

This commit contains various improvements to the tab painting classes that were
copied to the Windows LAF from FlatLAF in the previous commit. These particular
changes may later be ported back to FlatLAF if desired. In this commit, we do
not yet change the actual styling of the tabs.

Details:
* Align and connect borders between tabs and the container panel below,
  including on fractional HiDPI scalings (e.g. 150%). Some visual artifacts
  still exist, e.g. on 125% scaling, but they are less common, and not very
  visible.
* Improve the behavior of DPIUnscaledBorder in more cases.
* Add new configuration options to the TabDisplayerUI classes, to prepare for
  the new tab style on Windows, but do not yet make use of them. This includes
  the ability to draw a border around the selected tab, the ability to set a
  separate hover color for unselected tabs, and support for a color gradient in
  the selected editor tab.
* In editor tabs, avoid showing a tab separator after the last tab.
* In editor tabs, properly handle clipped tabs.
* In view tabs, properly allocate space for the animated "busy" icon.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jGauravGupta/netbeans/commits/684368f42bc4399d71b2d7ca6c872e3907f017f0"},{"sha":"df0cada60669664507d0266314d7b76728d92308","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Replace the bitmap 'busy' icon with a manually drawn spinner that scales well on HiDPI/Retina screens.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jGauravGupta/netbeans/commits/df0cada60669664507d0266314d7b76728d92308"},{"sha":"ad7eea77d996624caf520aa32cfced8250848882","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Adjust some borders on the Windows LAF, and other smaller tweaks.

* Apply previous border tweaks for HiDPI screens in a few more places, notably

unknown collection or structural types, Terraform would crash. We need
to detect unknown values before attempting to iterate them.

Change-Id: Ie35c222a30d257c4ef3226fb602abc0ef40fd6ff","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/elfringham/tensorflow/commits/d2abe16288dce4a730d4a13cb1ab6cdedfc6b998"},{"sha":"1f696e799119c70bbb1ed2b70500af5ece457f75","author":{"name":"Hanhan Wang","email":"17db91a825a40156b2c20ef2022824cbafd12aac@google.com"},"message":"Lowering mhlo.reduce_window to Linalg ops for dynamic shapes.

Also fixes the input shape for static test cases. E.g.,

```
  %0 = "mhlo.reduce_window"(%arg0, %arg1) ( {
  ^bb0(%arg2: tensor<f32>, %arg3 : tensor<f32>):
    %1 = mhlo.minimum %arg2, %arg3 : tensor<f32>
    "mhlo.return"(%1) : (tensor<f32>) -> ()
  }) {window_dimensions = dense<[1, 3, 3, 1]> : tensor<4xi64>,
      window_strides = dense<[1, 2, 2, 1]> : tensor<4xi64>} : (tensor<1x17x17x64xf32>, tensor<f32>) -> tensor<1x8x8x64xf32>
```

Look into dimension 1 where window_dim is 3 and window_stride is 2.
The reduction indices are [0, 3), [2, 5), ... , [14, 17).
In this case, 17 is enough for input size. The last element will never
get touched.

* [Offscreen] Mount/unmount layout effects

Exposes the Offscreen component type and implements basic support for
mount/unmounting layout effects when the visibility is toggled.

Mostly it works the same way as hidden Suspense trees, which use the
same internal fiber type. I had to add an extra bailout, though, that
doesn't apply to the Suspense case but does apply to Offscreen
components: a hidden Offscreen tree will eventually render at low
priority, and when we it does, its `subtreeTag` will have effects
scheduled on it. So I added a check to the layout phase where, if the
subtree is hidden, we skip over the subtree entirely. An alternate
design would be to clear the subtree flags in the render phase, but I
prefer doing it this way since it's harder to mess up.

We also need an API to enable the same thing for passive effects. This
is not yet implemented.

* Add test starting from hidden

* checkpoint save: update InternalValidate tests to compare exact error

* configschema: extract and extend attribute validation

This commit adds an attribute-specific InternalValidate which was extracted directly from the block.InternalValidate logic and extended to verify any NestedTypes inside an Attribute. Only one error message changed, since it is now valid to have a cty.NilType for Attribute.Type as long as NestedType is set.

* terraform: validate provider schema's during NewContext

We haven't been able to guarantee that providers are validating their own schemas using (some version of) InternalValidate since providers were split out of the main codebase. This PR adds a call to InternalValidate when provider schemas are initially loaded by NewContext, which required a few other changes:

InternalValidate's handling of errors vs multierrors was a little weird - before this PR, it was occasionally returning a non-nil error which only stated "0 errors occurred" - so I addressed that in InternalValidate. I then tested this with a configuration that was using all of our most popular providers, and found that at least on provider had some invalid attribute names, so I commented that particular validation out. Adding that in would be a breaking change which we would have to coordinate with enablement and providers and (especially in this case) make sure it's well communicated to external provider developers.

I ran a few very unscientific tests comparing the timing with and without this validation, and it appeared to only cause a sub-second increase.

* refactor validate error message to closer match the sdk's message

* better error message

* tweak error message: move the instruction to run init to the end of the message, after the specific error.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b9138f44652d9f24fd50f3a5ce4ffbe7b9acd9c7"},{"sha":"3722b1b6130cfaec5544c0b05a64d979fe22ddd1","author":{"name":"Matthew Frahry","email":"96854ef89bcb7433eddb7599cc03fd0a52d7b57f@gmail.com"},"message":"backend/azurerm: support for using azuread authentication for blobs","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/3722b1b6130cfaec5544c0b05a64d979fe22ddd1"},{"sha":"3546650ac6e8c5f2e85efd5d6c8bb7aee4ba3150","author":{"name":"Matthew Frahry","email":"96854ef89bcb7433eddb7599cc03fd0a52d7b57f@gmail.com"},"message":"backend/azurerm: adding the right role name","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/3546650ac6e8c5f2e85efd5d6c8bb7aee4ba3150"},{"sha":"0bc64e3cc462e0ced0b4760ce1eda23f7f0c361e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"1d268a46cac434886194f031dd61c091838d2d63@hashicorp.com"},"message":"tests for destroy-then-update dependency ordering","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/0bc64e3cc462e0ced0b4760ce1eda23f7f0c361e"},{"sha":"dcb12195a306c4cda64a2c941ea7d40cfe149603","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"1d268a46cac434886194f031dd61c091838d2d63@hashicorp.com"},"message":"update destroying.md

[{"sha":"c047958b5708e4f500fe61000a662c169d048fff","author":{"name":"Kevin Burke","email":"ffb4761cba839470133bee36aeb139f58d7dbaa9@meter.com"},"message":"go.mod,backend: update coreos/etcd dependency to release-3.4 branch

etcd rewrote its import path from coreos/etcd to go.etcd.io/etcd.
Changed the imports path in this commit, which also updates the code
version.

This lets us remove the github.com/ugorji/go/codec dependency, which
was pinned to a fairly old version. The net change is a loss of 30,000
lines of code in the vendor directory. (I first noticed this problem
because the outdated go/codec dependency was causing a dependency
failure when I tried to put Terraform and another project in the same
vendor directory.)

Note the version shows up funkily in go.mod, but I verified

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385560452
Change-Id: I5b19c1a78a71e3e6e33689e1576693b78ae0543a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/fc55e3af01e239b0fcdf9d9e6c21cf99476feb29"},{"sha":"cf8a6bd57e9215f7d1d3face5a5e1fb78828c122","author":{"name":"Tim Shen","email":"4730ecb3b3122c1a4c40822c62fa6d402a094d1b@google.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Generate `lmhlo.fusion { mhlo.some_op }` instead of `lmhlo.some_op`, for most of the ops.

This simplifies the emitter for quite a bit, as kCopy and kReduce emitters now don't have to deal with unnested cases.

This also simplifies XLA HLO -> LMHLO conversion, since now there are much less kinds of LMHLO ops to be converted.

Per chat discussion between sanjoy@, jurahul@ and me, we think it's a good idea to move away from LMHLO and only use lmhlo.fusion + MHLO. This way, lmhlo.fusion effectively just acts as a composable bufferization annotation.

This CL is a preliminary experiment for that plan, as it removes some uses from XLA/GPU. Once we are confident about this approach, we can officially propose the deprecation and removal of LMHLO (except for .fusion).

Signed-off-by: Arko Dasgupta <arko.dasgupta@docker.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/awesomebytes/moby/commits/cd864b50a27a20603d1ab14c590d81b521d47cc1"},{"sha":"fcb70a0e864b7da1e0f2ab10d9666bfddd4e7b19","author":{"name":"Su Wang","email":"878e316590ff649aff16c893ccad5fed35070e35@docker.com"},"message":"DOCKER-USER chain not created when IPTableEnable=false.

This fix addresses https://docker.atlassian.net/browse/ENGCORE-1115
Expected behaviors upon docker engine restarts:
1. IPTableEnable=true, DOCKER-USER chain present
   -- no change to DOCKER-USER chain
2. IPTableEnable=true, DOCKER-USER chain not present
   -- DOCKER-USER chain created and inserted top of FORWARD
      chain.
3. IPTableEnable=false, DOCKER-USER chain present
   -- no change to DOCKER-USER chain
      the rational is that DOCKER-USER is populated
      and may be used by end-user for purpose other than
      filtering docker container traffic. Thus even if
      IPTableEnable=false, docker engine does not touch
      pre-existing DOCKER-USER chain.
4. IPTableEnable=false, DOCKER-USER chain not present
   -- DOCKER-USER chain is not created.

Added document describing libnetwork traffic flow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/awesomebytes/moby/commits/1473794fb52e2dcfebff841bb3a92b52e7244ff1"},{"sha":"8899d916c070d2b5f6b35eb69bb3997217881b0f","author":{"name":"Andrew Kim","email":"1efc9ca9752ff84b9c48e9be50603182b6e58f9b@gmail.com"},"message":"Improving load balancer performance

IPVS module used for swarm load balancer had a performance issue
under a high load situation. conn_reuse_mode=0 sysctl variable can
be set to handle the high load situation by reusing existing
connection entries in the IPVS table.

Under a high load, IPVS module was dropping tcp SYN packets whenever
a port reuse is detected with a connection in TIME_WAIT status forcing
clients to re-initiate tcp connections after request timeout events.
By setting conn_reuse_mode=0, IPVS module avoids special handling of
existing entries in the IPVS connection table.
Along with expire_nodest_conn=1, swarm load balancer can handle
a high load of requests and forward connections to newly joining
backend services.

Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Fix bug where operands were incorrectly replaced for outside compiled ops with dynamic shapes.

This occurred when an outside compiled op with non-dynamic output came before another outside compiled op with a dynamic output.  For example:

%7 = "tf.E"(%4, %3) {_xla_outside_compilation = "auto"} : (tensor<?xi32>, tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<2xi32>)
%8 = "tf.F"(%7) : (tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<2xi32>)
%9 = "tf.G"(%8, %4, %3) {_xla_outside_compilation = "auto"} : (tensor<2xi32>, tensor<?xi32>, tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<?xi32>)

In this case, the second op should have all of the inputs sent to host through XlaHostCompute op so that shape inference works correctly.  With the bug, the statically shaped inputs were provided by communication for the earlier outside compilation op.  This lead to overwriting the value in the earlier op leading to a "operand #1 does not dominate this use" error.

The code is still at its early stage and currently only Linux is supported. A number of tests are disabled through `no_oss` tag because they don't pass in open-source yet.

Relevant new directories:
- ///tensorflow/compiler/mlir/...: MLIR Lowering passes that can convert TF Graphs (e.g. HLO) to BEF (Binary Executable Format) which can be executed by TFRT BEF Executor.
- //tensorflow/core/runtime_fallback/...: Runtime components that allow TFRT leverage OpKernels defined in current TensorFlow Runtime.

With this change, XLA GPU can lower a subset of thunks from mlir assembly using the lmhlo_gpu dialect to tfrt_gpu dialect, and then execute the corresponding BEF function. Notable tests:

```
bazel test --config=experimental_enable_bef_thunk \
  //tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests:mlir_gemm_test \
  //tensorflow/compiler/xla/tests:dot_operation_test_gpu
```

[{"sha":"487924576efac4fb257ae480ddeba534779633ec","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Fix issue where disabling TensorFloat-32 had no effect.

The issue was the tensor_float_32_enabled global variable was being linked in the binary twice. Disabling TensorFloat-32 changed one version of the global variable, and OpKernels checking TensorFloat-32 looked at the other version of the global variable. @penpornk helped find the fix.

I confirmed this change fixes the issue when applied to commit 2903b0a7d133a15d71d513df826386dc28d0631f. Unfortunately, the tests did not catch this issue, as the test case in config_test.py currently only supports Ampere and is skipped for non-Ampere GPUs (TensorFloat-32 only supports Ampere). I will later add a test that will catch such issues even when run on non-Ampere GPUs.

I plan on cherry-picking this change into TF 2.6.

Co-authored-by: Penporn Koanantakool‎ <penporn@google.com>

Rationale:

1. Equivalent functionality is already non-experimental
in the TF Lite C API via the TfLiteIntepreterOptionsAddDelegate
function.

2. This is a more principled alternative to
Interpreter::ModifyGraphWithDelegate, which is widely used; it is more
principled because it does not require mutating the Interpreter after
it has been created, and mutating operations make things harder to
reason about.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385809361
Change-Id: I0964b6a5c57d56c30e37022e504af93f744e5d5a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/37f7b2853a48ee5f49b111667ad80360bec04a3e"},{"sha":"6bdec787aa1e31cce712f8fd31a91b8902988f52","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Fix bug where operands were incorrectly replaced for outside compiled ops with dynamic shapes.

This occurred when an outside compiled op with non-dynamic output came before another outside compiled op with a dynamic output.  For example:

%7 = "tf.E"(%4, %3) {_xla_outside_compilation = "auto"} : (tensor<?xi32>, tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<2xi32>)
%8 = "tf.F"(%7) : (tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<2xi32>)
%9 = "tf.G"(%8, %4, %3) {_xla_outside_compilation = "auto"} : (tensor<2xi32>, tensor<?xi32>, tensor<2xi32>) -> (tensor<?xi32>)

In this case, the second op should have all of the inputs sent to host through XlaHostCompute op so that shape inference works correctly.  With the bug, the statically shaped inputs were provided by communication for the earlier outside compilation op.  This lead to overwriting the value in the earlier op leading to a "operand #1 does not dominate this use" error.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385492367
Change-Id: I668b618e7b18abed199b445641b469069f35de2f","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/1bec81a9f28005ef2e5cc9f3063fd62ce3272bdf"},{"sha":"62db2e9b5b3ed8c28a3170b0961480008048f4d0","author":{"name":"George Necula","email":"ff41ff8c67a16b3c7c1ec22e97a29c6fe4506fc6@google.com"},"message":"[host_callback] Increase number of threads for callback processing.

Previously there was one thread per device for receiving the outfeed from
devices, but there was a single global thread that was calling into the Python
callbacks. This meant that if one of the callbacks was slow, it was blocking
processing of all other callbacks.

One situation when this created difficulties was if one wanted to break a host_callback into two operations: a quick one to enqueue work on a threadpool,
and a subsequent slow one to wait for and retreive the result. The first slow callback would block all other callbacks, including possibly some quick ones, thus missing the opportunity to start the slow work.

With this change there is a separate queue of outfeeds for each device and a
separate thread per device to call into Python. This allows for concurrency
between callbacks from different devices, although the callbacks from one
device are still sequential. If the programmer wants more concurrency, they can use a threadpool. Having more concurrency by default is tricky, because it may mean that the Python callbacks for one device may be seen out of order.

[{"sha":"3cea30ab6c9e6d05e7b865972737b3efd7c4a63c","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Open-source TensorFlow's TFRT backend.

The code is still at its early stage and currently only Linux is supported. A number of tests are disabled through `no_oss` tag because they don't pass in open-source yet.

Relevant new directories:
- ///tensorflow/compiler/mlir/...: MLIR Lowering passes that can convert TF Graphs (e.g. HLO) to BEF (Binary Executable Format) which can be executed by TFRT BEF Executor.
- //tensorflow/core/runtime_fallback/...: Runtime components that allow TFRT leverage OpKernels defined in current TensorFlow Runtime.

With this change, XLA GPU can lower a subset of thunks from mlir assembly using the lmhlo_gpu dialect to tfrt_gpu dialect, and then execute the corresponding BEF function. Notable tests:

```
bazel test --config=experimental_enable_bef_thunk \
  //tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests:mlir_gemm_test \
  //tensorflow/compiler/xla/tests:dot_operation_test_gpu
```

Also fix Canonicalization of TFR_QuantQParams op to emit TF_ConstOp directly.
The existing canonicalization lowers QuantQParams op to std.constant -> tfr.constant_tensor op. This pattern is eventually canonicalized into tf.Const -> tfr.cast ops, so emitting tf.Const -> tfr.cast ops directly will improve simplicity.

Minor fix: moved functions into anonymous namespace when possible.

Change-Id: I5b19c1a78a71e3e6e33689e1576693b78ae0543a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/tensorflow/commits/fc55e3af01e239b0fcdf9d9e6c21cf99476feb29"},{"sha":"cf8a6bd57e9215f7d1d3face5a5e1fb78828c122","author":{"name":"Tim Shen","email":"4730ecb3b3122c1a4c40822c62fa6d402a094d1b@google.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Generate `lmhlo.fusion { mhlo.some_op }` instead of `lmhlo.some_op`, for most of the ops.

This simplifies the emitter for quite a bit, as kCopy and kReduce emitters now don't have to deal with unnested cases.

This also simplifies XLA HLO -> LMHLO conversion, since now there are much less kinds of LMHLO ops to be converted.

Per chat discussion between sanjoy@, jurahul@ and me, we think it's a good idea to move away from LMHLO and only use lmhlo.fusion + MHLO. This way, lmhlo.fusion effectively just acts as a composable bufferization annotation.

This CL is a preliminary experiment for that plan, as it removes some uses from XLA/GPU. Once we are confident about this approach, we can officially propose the deprecation and removal of LMHLO (except for .fusion).

Split some parts of NativeInterpreterWrapper which depend on experimental APIs
into a separate derived class NativeInterpreterWrapperExperimental,
and don't include that derived class in the "stable" build targets.

In particular NativeInterpreterWrapper.resetVariableTensors depends on
the C++ Interpreter::ResetVariableTensors method, which is experimental,
so we want to avoid depending on that from the "stable" build targets.

(Note that parts which depend on Interpreter::ModifyGraphWithDelegate
have NOT been moved to NativeInterpreterWrapperExperimental. The tentative
plan for those is to instead refactor them to use InterpreterBuilder::AddDelegate, and to promote that API to stable, in subsequent CLs.)

Change-Id: I8a3e0ef9e573b75b9429facda0fc4fb2e92a869a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/c891adef52607b9c65bb190fb55d794a95fe30e8"},{"sha":"69fc036bb636ea7f76d4b4d879e27f7e4cf0ad33","author":{"name":"Peng Wang","email":"b55f18ff6423501a9509f40f9539fd4a14e4c9f9@google.com"},"message":"Adds automatic ref-counting (on the underlying resource) to ResourceHandle.

This CL adds an option for ResourceHandle to hold on to a pointer to a resource, in which case the ResourceHandle will call `Ref` on the resource when the handle is copied, and call `Unref` on the resource when the handle is destroyed. This feature will serve as an automatic life-cycle management system for resources.

Resources under this life-cycle management system will bypass ResourceMgr.

This CL doesn't opt in any existing resources to this new life-cycle management system. Follow-up CLs will opt them in gradually.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 385560452
Change-Id: I5b19c1a78a71e3e6e33689e1576693b78ae0543a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/fc55e3af01e239b0fcdf9d9e6c21cf99476feb29"},{"sha":"cf8a6bd57e9215f7d1d3face5a5e1fb78828c122","author":{"name":"Tim Shen","email":"4730ecb3b3122c1a4c40822c62fa6d402a094d1b@google.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Generate `lmhlo.fusion { mhlo.some_op }` instead of `lmhlo.some_op`, for most of the ops.

This simplifies the emitter for quite a bit, as kCopy and kReduce emitters now don't have to deal with unnested cases.

This also simplifies XLA HLO -> LMHLO conversion, since now there are much less kinds of LMHLO ops to be converted.

Per chat discussion between sanjoy@, jurahul@ and me, we think it's a good idea to move away from LMHLO and only use lmhlo.fusion + MHLO. This way, lmhlo.fusion effectively just acts as a composable bufferization annotation.

This CL is a preliminary experiment for that plan, as it removes some uses from XLA/GPU. Once we are confident about this approach, we can officially propose the deprecation and removal of LMHLO (except for .fusion).

Signed-off-by: Xia Wu <xwumzn@amazon.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/d10046f228e4152b12bb6ce7db0008f227b95790"},{"sha":"00a4f67ddf78883bb6e891ec3943de08564e209d","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Reduce TestClientWithRequestTimeout flakiness

The test sometimes failed because no error was returned:

    === Failed
    === FAIL: pkg/plugins TestClientWithRequestTimeout (0.00s)
         client_test.go:254: assertion failed: expected an error, got nil: expected error

Possibly caused by a race condition, as the sleep was just 1 ms longer than the timeout;
this patch is increasing the sleep in the response to try to reduce flakiness.

Upstream update fixes the issue where left node would be marked as

Signed-off-by: Roman Volosatovs <roman.volosatovs@docker.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/cdd04a94bcbd33edac73bb945f57c2e21fed7641"},{"sha":"2837fba75f5ee7e57c167af4e70569adaf59377a","author":{"name":"Roman Volosatovs","email":"de37379432a0923e9d62232e7753800cfd82d951@docker.com"},"message":"libnetwork: ensure all nodes are available in tests

`github.com/hashicorp/memberlist` update caused `TestNetworkDBCRUDTableEntries`
to occasionally fail, because the test would try to check whether an entry
write is propagated to all nodes, but it would not wait for all nodes to
be available before performing the write.
It could be that the failure is caused simply by improved performance of
the dependency - it could also be that some connectivity guarantee the
test depended on is not provided by the dependency anymore.
The same fix is applied to `TestNetworkDBNodeJoinLeaveIteration` due to
same issue.

The "quiet" argument was only used in a single place (at daemon startup), and
every other use had to pass "false" to prevent this function from logging
warnings.

Now that SysInfo contains the warnings that occurred when collecting the
system information, we can make leave it up to the caller to use those
warnings (and log them if wanted).
